ive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107074814/http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=41449 |archive-date=2012-11-07 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|-\n|| #12\n|| October 2012\n|| 171,438\n|| 2\n|| <ref name=\"OctoberSales\" />\n|-\n|}\n\n====''AVX: VS''====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=10%| Issue\n!width=30%| First month of publication\n!width=30%| Estimated no. of units sold\n!width=20%| Sales chart position\n!width=10%| Ref.\n|-\n|| #1\n|| April 2012\n|| 103,436\n|| 4\n|| <ref name=\"AprilSales\" />\n|-\n|| #2\n|| May 2012\n|| 98,812\n|| 6\n|| <ref name=\"MaySales\" />\n|-\n|| #3\n|| June 2012\n|| 94,530\n|| 10\n|| <ref name=\"JuneSales\" />\n|-\n|| #4\n|| July 2012\n|| 86,538\n|| 7\n|| <ref name=\"JulySales\" />\n|-\n|| #5\n|| August 2012\n|| 78,381 \n|| 7\n|| <ref name=\"AugustSales\" />\n|-\n|| #6\n|| October 2012\n|| 75,292\n|| 8\n|| <ref name=\"OctoberSales\" />\n|}\n\n====''AVX: Consequences''====\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:auto; text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!width=10%| Issue\n!width=30%| First month of publication\n!width=30%| Estimated no. of units sold\n!width=20%| Sales chart position\n!width=10%| Ref.\n|-\n|| #1\n|rowspan=\"4\"| October 2012\n|| 73,266\n|| 10\n|rowspan=\"4\"| <ref name=\"OctoberSales\" />\n|-\n|| #2\n|| 62,794\n|| 16\n|-\n|| #3\n|| 59,891\n|| 20\n|-\n|| #4\n|| 58,522\n|| 22\n|-\n|| #5\n|| November 2012 \n|| 58,474\n|| 31\n|| <ref>{{cite web |first=John |last=Mayo |date=2012-12-11 |url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article&id=42614 |title=Sales Estimates for November, 2012 - \"All-New X-Men\" Leads Marvel NOW! Sales Domination |website=Comic Book Resources |accessdate=2012-12-11 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6DVb9UDNQ?url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/?page=article |archive-date=2013-01-08 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Other versions==\n\n===''A-Babies vs. X-Babies''===\nIn Marvelous Meadows, as baby Steve Roger says good night to all of his [[teddy bear]]s, he notices that baby Scott Summers from across the street has taken Bucky Bear. In response, Baby Steve assembles his fellow Avengers while Baby Scott brings together his team of X-Babies and the two teams fight in the middle of the street. After a series of turnovers, the Phoenix appears and demands that Baby Scott return Bucky Bear to Baby Steve. When he refuses, the Phoenix causes a giant explosion. The next morning, Baby Steve's parents find him sleeping peacefully with Bucky Bear, except now there is a giant hole in his room and a crater in the middle of the street.<ref>''A-Babies vs. X-Babies'' #1</ref>\n\n===''What If?''===\nAs the Phoenix Force heads towards Earth, the Guardians of the Galaxy manage to send a warning before they are destroyed by it. Having received the warning, The Avengers send a team into space as a first line of defense, while others go to Utopia to take Hope Summers, the intended host of the Phoenix Force, into custody. Upon arrival, Magneto, Hope, Namor and Storm discuss the situation with the Avengers. After a heated exchange, Wolverine attacks Namor and fatally injures Storm in the process. In retaliation, Magneto brings down the Avengers helicarrier.<ref>''What if? AVX'' #1</ref>\n\nAs the helicarrier falls, Hope, Magneto and Emma Frost leave to intercept the Phoenix Force on the Moon. In space, Thor manages to wound the Phoenix Force and it offers the remaining Avengers its gift but then senses Hope and merges with her instead, transforming Hope into Phoenix.<ref>''What if? AVX'' #2</ref>\n\nOnce the transformation is complete, Hope sends The Avengers back to Earth while she considers her options. Magneto convinces Hope that humans are a threat, over Emma's protests. After Emma warns X-Men and The Avengers, Black Panther attempts an unsuccessful suicide attack on Hope and Magneto. Hope kills Emma for her betrayal and sends a meteor shower to Earth, destroying major cities. Hope and Magneto then confront the other X-Men, offering to spare their lives if they join them.<ref>''What if? AVX'' #3</ref>\n\nThe X-Men and The Avengers attack Hope and Magneto. As the battle continues, the power starts overwhelming Hope and she begs Magneto for help. Magneto kills Hope and the power transfers to him. However, Wolverine manages to stab Magneto in the brain, killing him instantly. As all the others die, Wolverine is saved by Jean Grey, who returns as the White Phoenix. Jean takes Wolverine into a time bubble and together they watch as life is slowly restored.<ref>''What if? AVX'' #4</ref>\n\n==In other media==\nAn issue of ''Avengers vs. X-Men'' appears and is involved in the ''[[Once Upon a Time (TV series)|Once Upon a Time]]'' episode \"[[A Land Without Magic]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://marvel.com/news/story/18698/avx_on_once_upon_a_time_season_finale|title=AvX on Once Upon a Time Season Finale|date=8 May 2012|accessdate=10 May 2012|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6B9d9z6on?url=http://marvel.com/news/story/18698/avx_on_once_upon_a_time_season_finale|archive-date=4 October 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://marvel.com/avx Avengers vs. X-Men] at Marvel.com\n\n{{Avengers publications}}\n{{X-Men comics}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Related topics\n|list1=\n{{New Avengers}}\n}}\n{{Marvel events}}\n\n[[Category:Avengers (comics) storylines]]\n[[Category:X-Men storylines]]\n[[Category:Superhero comics]]\n[[Category:Avengers (comics) titles]]\n[[Category:X-Men titles]]\n[[Category:2012 comics debuts]]\n", "name_user": "TriiipleThreat", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAct 3\u00a0\u2013 \"There Can Only Be One\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avengers_vs._X-Men"}
{"title_page": "Itekoma Hits", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Itekoma Hits\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Otoboke Beaver]]\n| cover      = OtobokeBeaver_ItekomaHits.jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = {{Start date|2019|4|26|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Hardcore punk]]|[[noise rock]]|[[alternative rock]]}}\n| length     = 26:26\n| label      = [[Damnably]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = Okoshiyasu!! Otoboke Beaver\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\n'''''Itekoma Hits''''' is an album by the Japanese punk rock band [[Otoboke Beaver]], released by [[Damnably]] on 26 April 2019. The album features newly-recorded songs alongside tracks from the previously released EPs ''Bakuro Book'' (2016) and ''Love Is Short!!'' (2017).<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Julia|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2040994/stream-otoboke-beavers-album-itekoma-hits/music/album-stream/|title=Stream Otoboke Beaver\u2019s New Album Itekoma Hits|website=[[Stereogum]]|date=April 23, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The album's release was preceded by the single \"Anata Watashi Daita Ato Yome no Meshi\" which is also included on the album.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last=Phares|first=Heather|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/itekoma-hits-mw0003261517|title=Itekoma Hits \u2013 Otoboke Beaver|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev2score = 7.7/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Jagota|first=Vrinda|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/otoboke-beaver-itekoma-hits/|title=Otoboke Beaver: Itekoma Hits|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=April 29, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev3score = 7/10<ref name=\"PopMatters\">{{cite web|last=Conaton|first=Chris|url=https://www.popmatters.com/otoboke-beaver-is-loud-fast-and-fun-2638759691.html?rebelltitem=3|title=Otoboke Beaver Is Loud, Fast, and Fun on 'Itekoma Hits'|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=June 10, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n''Itekoma Hits'' received generally positive reviews from critics. [[AllMusic]] critic Heather Phares praised the band \"for making their pummeling attacks sound both furious and gleefully liberated\" and noted that the newly-recorded tracks \"add more detail and sophistication\" to the band's sound. Phares concluded that the album \"doesn't leave listeners a moment to catch their breath -- or grow bored.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the words of ''PunkNews'', \"The four women who make up Otoboke Beaver are so unbelievably talented and insane and frenetic that the twenty-seven or so minutes that make up this album grab you immediately and never let you go.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=nickEp|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/16632/otoboke-beaver-itekoma-hits|title=Otoboke Beaver \u2013 Itekoma Hits|website=Punknews.org|date=July 24, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>  \n\nVrinda Jagota of [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] described the album as \"a tornado of defiance\" and \"fueled by a rage so ferocious it\u2019s thrilling to behold.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Chris Conaton of ''[[PopMatters]]'' criticized the construction of some of the songs, but concluded that \"Even when they're angry, these women are clearly having a great time, and that enthusiasm makes for an infectious listening experience.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\nNote: (&Dagger;) indicates songs previously released on the EPs ''Bakuro Book'' (2016) and ''Love Is Short!!'' (2017). <br>\nNote: (&Dagger;&Dagger;) \"Akimahenka,\" (originally 2015) and \"Anata Watashi Daita Ato Yome no Meshi\" are new recordings of a previously released songs with Kahokiss replacing Pop on drums.\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Accorinrin\n| title1 = Datsu, Hikage no Onna\n| length1 = 2:04\n| title2 = Akimahenka\n| note2 = 2019 version &Dagger;&Dagger;\n| length2 = 1:13\n| title3 = S'il vous Plait\n| note3 = &Dagger;\n| length3 = 2:15\n| title4 = Bakuro Book\n| note4 = &Dagger;\n| length4 = 2:21\n| title5 = What Do You Mean You Have to Talk to Me at This Late Date?\n| note5 = &Dagger;\n| length5 = 1:54\n| title6 = Introduce Me to Your Family\n| note6 = &Dagger;\n| length6 = 2:28\n| title7 = Love Is Short!!\n| note7 = &Dagger;\n| length7 = 2:11\n| title8 = Bad Luck\n| length8 = 2:06\n| title9 = Don't Light My Fire\n| length9 = 2:16\n| title10 = 6 Day Working Week Is a Pain\n| length10 = 2:47\n| title11 = Binge Eating Binge Drinking Bulimia\n| length11 = 0:53\n| title12 = I'm Tired of Your Repeating Story\n| length12 = 1:43\n| title13 = Anata Watashi Daita Ato Yome no Meshi\n| note13 = &Dagger;&Dagger;\n| length13 = 1:57\n| title14 = Ikezu (Mean)\n| note14 = &Dagger;\n| length14 = 0:18\n| total_length = 26:26\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* Accorinrin \u2013 lead vocals, occasional rhythm guitar\n* Yoyoyoshie \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n* Hiro-Chan \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* Kahokiss \u2013 drums, backing vocals\n* Pop \u2013 drums, backing vocals (&Dagger;)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = Itekoma Hits\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Otoboke Beaver]]\n| cover      = OtobokeBeaver_ItekomaHits.jpg\n| alt        = \n| released   = {{Start date|2019|4|26|df=yes}}\n| recorded   = \n| studio     = \n| genre      = {{hlist|[[Hardcore punk]]|[[noise rock]]|[[alternative rock]]}}\n| length     = 26:26\n| label      = [[Damnably]]\n| producer   = \n| prev_title = Okoshiyasu!! Otoboke Beaver\n| prev_year  = 2018\n| next_title = \n| next_year  = \n}}\n\n'''''Itekoma Hits''''' is an album by the Japanese punk rock band [[Otoboke Beaver]], released by [[Damnably]] on 26 April 2019. The album features newly-recorded songs alongside tracks from the previously released EPs ''Bakuro Book'' (2016) and ''Love Is Short!!'' (2017).<ref>{{cite web|last=Gray|first=Julia|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2040994/stream-otoboke-beavers-album-itekoma-hits/music/album-stream/|title=Stream Otoboke Beaver\u2019s New Album Itekoma Hits|website=[[Stereogum]]|date=April 23, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref> The album's release was preceded by the single \"Anata Watashi Daita Ato Yome no Meshi\" which is also included on the album.\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|last=Phares|first=Heather|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/itekoma-hits-mw0003261517|title=Itekoma Hits \u2013 Otoboke Beaver|website=[[AllMusic]]|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev2score = 7.7/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|last=Jagota|first=Vrinda|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/otoboke-beaver-itekoma-hits/|title=Otoboke Beaver: Itekoma Hits|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=April 29, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev3score = 7/10<ref name=\"PopMatters\">{{cite web|last=Conaton|first=Chris|url=https://www.popmatters.com/otoboke-beaver-is-loud-fast-and-fun-2638759691.html?rebelltitem=3|title=Otoboke Beaver Is Loud, Fast, and Fun on 'Itekoma Hits'|website=[[PopMatters]]|date=June 10, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n''Itekoma Hits'' received generally positive reviews from critics. [[AllMusic]] critic Heather Phares praised the band \"for making their pummeling attacks sound both furious and gleefully liberated\" and noted that the newly-recorded tracks \"add more detail and sophistication\" to the band's sound. Phares concluded that the album \"doesn't leave listeners a moment to catch their breath -- or grow bored.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> In the words of ''PunkNews'', \"The four women who make up Otoboke Beaver are so unbelievably talented and insane and frenetic that the twenty-seven or so minutes that make up this album grab you immediately and never let you go.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=nickEp|url=https://www.punknews.org/review/16632/otoboke-beaver-itekoma-hits|title=Otoboke Beaver \u2013 Itekoma Hits|website=Punknews.org|date=July 24, 2019|access-date=September 24, 2019}}</ref>  \n\nVrinda Jagota of [[Pitchfork (website)|''Pitchfork'']] described the album as \"a tornado of defiance\" and \"fueled by a rage so ferocious it\u2019s thrilling to behold.\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork\"/> Chris Conaton of ''[[PopMatters]]'' criticized the construction of some of the songs, but concluded that \"Even when they're angry, these women are clearly having a great time, and that enthusiasm makes for an infectious listening experience.\"<ref name=\"PopMatters\"/>\n\n== Track listing ==\nNote: (&Dagger;) indicates songs previously released on the EPs ''Bakuro Book'' (2016) and ''Love Is Short!!'' (2017). Track 2, \"Akimahenka,\" is a new recording of a previously released song.\n\n{{Track listing\n| all_writing = Accorinrin\n| title1 = Datsu, Hikage no Onna\n| length1 = 2:04\n| title2 = Akimahenka\n| note2 = 2019 version\n| length2 = 1:13\n| title3 = S'il vous Plait\n| note3 = &Dagger;\n| length3 = 2:15\n| title4 = Bakuro Book\n| note4 = &Dagger;\n| length4 = 2:21\n| title5 = What Do You Mean You Have to Talk to Me at This Late Date?\n| note5 = &Dagger;\n| length5 = 1:54\n| title6 = Introduce Me to Your Family\n| note6 = &Dagger;\n| length6 = 2:28\n| title7 = Love Is Short!!\n| note7 = &Dagger;\n| length7 = 2:11\n| title8 = Bad Luck\n| length8 = 2:06\n| title9 = Don't Light My Fire\n| length9 = 2:16\n| title10 = 6 Day Working Week Is a Pain\n| length10 = 2:47\n| title11 = Binge Eating Binge Drinking Bulimia\n| length11 = 0:53\n| title12 = I'm Tired of Your Repeating Story\n| length12 = 1:43\n| title13 = Anata Watashi Daita Ato Yome no Meshi\n| length13 = 1:57\n| title14 = Ikezu (Mean)\n| note14 = &Dagger;\n| length14 = 0:18\n| total_length = 26:26\n}}\n\n== Personnel ==\n* Accorinrin \u2013 lead vocals, occasional rhythm guitar\n* Yoyoyoshie \u2013 guitar, backing vocals\n* Hiro-Chan \u2013 bass, backing vocals\n* Kahokiss \u2013 drums, backing vocals\n* Pop \u2013 drums, backing vocals (&Dagger;)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2019 albums]]\n", "name_user": "Blazinggunny", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTrack listing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Itekoma_Hits"}
{"title_page": "Jason Nash", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor, writer, director, comedian, podcaster, and YouTube personality}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name        = Jason Nash\n| image        = Jason Nash.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   =  Jason Eric Nash\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|2000|05|23}}<ref>{{cite tweet|user=DavidDobrik|author=DAVID DOBRIK|number=867165980513849344|date=23 May 2017|title=Happy birthday to one of my favorite seniors. Thank you for letting me broadcast your mid life crisis to the world}}</ref>\n| birth_place  = [[Boston]], [[Massachusetts]], U.S.\n| occupation   = {{flatlist|\n* Actor\n* YouTube personality\n}} \n| spouse       =  Marney Hochman (divorced)\n| years_active = 2016\u2013present\n| subscribers= 2.5 million (Jason Nash) <br> 218k (Jason Nash Family)\n| views=405 million (Jason Nash) <br> 9.7 million (Jason Nash Family)\n| network = Collab\n| associated_acts =* [[Josh Peck]]\n* [[David Dobrik & \"The Vlog Squad\"|David Dobrik]]\n* [[Trisha Paytas]]\n* [[Gabbie Hanna]]\n* [[Liza Koshy]]\n* [[JoJo Siwa]]\n| silver_button=yes\n| silver_year=2017\n|gold_button=yes\n|gold_year=2018\n| stats_update = {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTDAY}}, {{CURRENTYEAR}}\n| alma_mater    = \n}}\n\n'''Jason Eric Nash''' (born May 23, 1973) is an American actor and [[YouTube]] personality. Best known for his channel on [[Vine (service)|Vine]], he was also a semi-finalist on ''[[Last Comic Standing]]'' in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jason Nash on Last Comic Standing|url=http://tvgeekarmy.com/post/viewpost/last-comic-standing-week-five-monkey-at-the-controls|website=TVGeekArmy.com|accessdate=July 11, 2010}}</ref> In 2016, Nash co-produced and starred in the movie, ''FML'' alongside friend and fellow YouTuber Brandon Calvillo.\n\n==Career==\nJason Nash moved to Los Angeles with the aspiration of becoming a comedian. Years into his life in Los Angeles, Nash built a presence on Vine and had over two million followers.<ref>(n.d.). Retrieved from https://vine.co/JasonNash/</ref> This was his first crack at the social media world, before becoming a YouTuber later on in his career.  Nash trained with the [[Upright Citizens Brigade]] and started his career as a member of the sketch troupe \"Price, Nash and Blieden\". The trio developed television shows for [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] and [[NBC]] and were chosen three times to perform at the [[Aspen Comedy Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Nash with Upright Citizens Brigade|url=http://www.cc.com/shows/upright-citizens-brigade|publisher=Comedy Central}}</ref>\n\nNash wrote, directed and starred in his [[Comedy Central]] web series \"Jason Nash Is Married\", which was based on his one-man show \"In the Land of Tall Buildings and Red Fire Engines\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-jason-nash-is-married-review-20140905-story.html|title=Fun 'Jason Nash Is Married' explores love and showbiz|last=Goldstein|first=Gary|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> A film version of \"Jason Nash Is Married\" was released in 2014 starring [[Busy Philipps]].<ref>{{Citation|last=Nash|first=Jason|title=Jason Nash Is Married|date=2014-06-24|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt3737782/|others=Jason Nash, Busy Philipps, Casey Wilson|accessdate=2018-04-06}}</ref> Nash also created the web series \"How to Be a Man and The Shaman\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thelaughbutton.com/interviews/jason-nash-says-fml-new-indie-comedy/|title=Jason Nash says \"FML\" in his new indie comedy -|website=thelaughbutton.com|language=en-US|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> In 2016, Nash starred and directed his own screenplay, a road trip comedy film \"FML\" featuring fellow Vine star Brandon Calvillo.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/jason-nash-brandon-calvillo-fml-vine-1201743390/|title=Vine Stars Jason Nash, Brandon Calvillo Join Road Trip Comedy \u2018FML\u2019 (EXCLUSIVE)|last=McNary|first=Dave|date=2016-03-31|work=Variety|access-date=2018-04-06|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nNash co-created the long-running podcast \"Guys with Feelings\" which debuted in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jason Nash, a Guy with Feelings|url=http://laist.com/2008/12/11/interview_jason_nash.php|publisher=laist.com|accessdate=11 December 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081214135920/http://laist.com/2008/12/11/interview_jason_nash.php|archivedate=14 December 2008}}</ref> He has developed shows for Fox, NBC,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0621738/|title=Jason Nash|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref> [[CBS]], [[Oxygen (TV channel)|Oxygen]] and IFC. He has also acted in various shows including an opening of ''[[House MD]]'' episode 'The Tyrant', ''[[The Simpsons]]'' and ''[[Drake & Josh]].''  Nash is currently a YouTube [[vlogger]], and has over 2.5 million subscribers on his main channel.<ref>U. (n.d.). JasonNashComedy YouTube Stats, Channel Statistics. Retrieved from https://socialblade.com/youtube/user/jasonnashcomedy</ref> Nash became a Youtube Vlogger after being discovered by fellow Viner, [[David Dobrik & \"The Vlog Squad\"|David Dobrik]], one night at a comedy club. He began his Youtube career as a character in David Dobrik's vlogs, and soon began to upload his own videos. His first video was uploaded on December 2, 2016.<ref>Nash, J. (2016, December 02). Retrieved November 01, 2018, from https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ubgAC-5wF2A</ref>\n\nNash also runs a weekly podcast named \"Views\" with fellow YouTube personality David Dobrik. During its debut in 2017, \"Views\" climbed to #3 on the iTunes charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://shortyawards.com/10th/jasonnash|title=Jason Nash - The Shorty Awards|website=shortyawards.com|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>  Jason Nash and David Dobrik also took their podcast on a live tour across the US in summer of 2018, with their fellow youtube friends, called the \"Vlog Squad\".<ref>VIEWS SUMMER TOUR 2018. (n.d.). Retrieved from http://viewstour.com/</ref> They called it the \"VIEWS\" Tour. This included performances from other Youtubers such as Scotty Sire, live stories and a live Q&A session.<ref>Weiss, G. (2018, May 15). Vlogger/Podcasters David Dobrik And Jason Nash To Kick Off Summer Tour. Retrieved from https://www.tubefilter.com/2018/05/15/david-dobrik-and-jason-nash-views-tour/</ref>  Nash has stated that he is focused on Youtube as his career and because of this he uploads multiple times a week. For approximately one year, Nash had a second channel titled \"Jason Nash Family\" dedicated to his life with his children, Charley and Wyatt.<ref>(n.d.). Retrieved November 01, 2018, from https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCWcVikU5Sv-AqMtjV-BVsLQ</ref> This channel was later shut down by the request of his ex-wife Marney, who requested that the children would not be on the internet in such a drastic way. Because of this, Nash has put all his attention to his main Youtube channel.\n\n==Personal life==\nNash graduated from [[Medfield High School]] in 1991 and then attended college at the [[University of Massachusetts Amherst]]. After he left college, he worked as an assistant to [[Norm Macdonald]] on  ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''. Nash moved to Hollywood in 2001 when he was cast on the sketch show Random Play for [[VH1]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/arts/how-jason-nash-makes-a-living-in-web-series-4254799|title=How Jason Nash Makes a Living in Web Series|last=Carrie|first=Stephanie|date=2014-02-18|work=L.A. Weekly|access-date=2018-04-06}}</ref>\n\nHe was in a relationship with fellow Youtuber [[Trisha Paytas]]. The couple began dating in 2018, but were reported to have separated in February 2019.<ref>{{cite web|work=[[Newsweek]]|url=https://www.newsweek.com/trisha-paytas-david-dobrik-twitter-jason-nash-1317335|title=YouTuber Trisha Paytas Calls Out David Dobrik and Vlog Squad for Manipulation|date=February 4, 2019|author=Asarch, Steven|archive-url=https://archive.today/20190527031338/https://www.newsweek.com/trisha-paytas-david-dobrik-twitter-jason-nash-1317335|archive-date=May 27, 2019|access-date=August 25, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2019, fellow YouTuber [[David Dobrik]] legally married Lorraine Nash, Nash's mother, as a [[Sketch comedy|bit]] for one of his vlogs. On June 12, 2019, Dobrik announced that he and Lorraine had decided to end their marriage after one month. On November 22, 2019, Dobrik stated via Instagram that he has officially signed divorce papers and divorced Nash.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Television and film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Drake & Josh]]''\n| Waiter\n|\n|-\n| 2009\n| ''[[House (TV series)|House]]''\n| Neighbor\n|\n|-\n|2007\u20132010\n|''[[SuperNews!]]''\n| Multiple Characters \n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''Jason Nash is Married''\n| Jason Nash\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[The Simpsons]]''\n| Southie Criminals / Philantrophic Southies \n| Season 28, Episode 3: \"[[The Town (The Simpsons)|The Town]]\"\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/JasonNashComedy Jason Nash Comedy YouTube Channel]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nash, Jason}}\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:Writers from Boston]]\n[[Category:21st-century American comedians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American YouTubers]]\n[[Category:1973 births]]\n[[Category:Vine celebrities]]\n[[Category:Male YouTubers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor, writer, director, comedian, podcaster, and YouTube personality}}\n{{unreliable sources|date=October 2016}}\n\n{{Infobox YouTube personality\n| name        = Jason Nash\n| image        = Jason Nash.jpg\n| image_size   = \n| caption      = \n| birth_name   =  Jason Eric Nash\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1973|05